6.  We need to establish that `AEMeasurable X P` from `hX`.
7.  The definition of `AEMeasurable` is `∀ s ∈ BorelSets, {ω | X ω ∈ s} ∈ measurableSet`.
8.  Since `X` has the distribution `Ber(u, p)`, which is a product measure, `X` is indeed AEMeasurable.
9.  Once we have `AEMeasurable X P`, we can derive `AEMeasurable (fun ω => u \ X ω) P` using the properties of AEMeasurable sets (specifically, that the preimage of a set under a set difference is measurable if the original sets are measurable).

